// GAP-2 (HIGH) — `--no-strict-mmio` drops the runtime alignment check
//
// Per CLAUDE.md: `--no-strict-mmio` "allows @inttoptr without mmio
// declarations." When NO mmio ranges are declared and the flag is
// passed, the alignment check is also dropped — variable-address
// `@inttoptr` emits the raw cast `((uint32_t*)(uintptr_t)(addr))`
// with NO check at all.
//
// Verify with the emission diff (NOTE: this file has NO mmio range
// declaration, mimicking the user's "I don't want to declare every
// peripheral up front" use case):
//
//   zerc this.zer --no-strict-mmio --emit-c -o /tmp/a.c
//     -> grep "_zer_trap" /tmp/a.c around the @inttoptr line
//     -> NO range check (expected — flag relaxes range strictness)
//     -> NO alignment check (UNEXPECTED — alignment is per-load
//        per-target-type, not specific to mmio decl)
//
// The alignment check is a property of the target pointer type
// (`*u32` requires 4-byte alignment, `*u64` requires 8) — not of
// the mmio range. Dropping it under `--no-strict-mmio` is the
// silent failure mode this gap documents.
//
// On Cortex-M0/M0+ a misaligned `volatile *u32` load BusFaults at
// runtime. The trap is documented as a `_zer_trap("unaligned
// address")` ZER trap (with source line); the flag silently
// degrades it to a hardware fault.

i32 external_addr() { return 0x40000000; }

i32 main() {
    i32 addr = external_addr();
    volatile *u32 reg = @inttoptr(*u32, addr);
    return 0;
}
